title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q001
backText: A catalyst is a substance that reduces the activation energy of a chemical reaction, making the reaction possible and increasing its speed.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q002
backText: An enzyme is a protein that catalyzes a chemical reaction.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q003
backText: DNA carries hereditary information that controls the protein synthesis in living organisms.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q005
backText: A prokaryotic cell is a cell that doesn’t have an enclosed nucleus.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q006
backText: A eukaryotic cell is a cell with a nucleus enclosed in a membrane.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q007
frontText: What are the three main parts of a eukaryotic cell?
backText: The three main parts of a eukaryotic cell are the cell membrane, cytoplasm, and the nucleus.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q008
frontText: The mathematical formula for gravity is _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q009
frontText: The system of measurement that’s based on a decimal system of multiples and fractions of ten is called _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q010
frontText: Animals that eat plants and meat are called _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q011
frontText: The brain is part of what body system?
backText: The brain is part of the nervous system.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q012
frontText: Bones, joints, tendons, and cartilage are part of what body system?
backText: Bones, joints, tendons, and cartilage are part of the skeletal system.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q013
frontText: The muscles that control your voluntary movements are what kind of muscle?
backText: Skeletal muscle controls your voluntary movements.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q014
frontText: Plants can reproduce in what two ways?
backText: Plants can reproduce sexually and asexually.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q015
frontText: In human genetics, a healthy person has _____ pairs of chromosomes.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q016
frontText: What is the method by which scientists develop and test theories called?
backText: The method by which scientists develop and test theories is called the scientific method.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q017
frontText: What is the smallest part of an element that still retains the characteristics of that element?
backText: An atom is the smallest part of an element that still retains the characteristics of the element.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q018
frontText: Particles with no charge are called _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q021
frontText: An element’s atomic number corresponds with _____.
backText: the number of protons it has

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q022
frontText: What are the states of matter?
backText: Solid, liquid, and gas are the states of matter.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q023
frontText: When a substance transforms from a gas to a liquid, it goes through the process called _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q024
frontText: Elements joined by chemical bonds in a specific ratio are called _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q025
frontText: The process that rearranges a substance’s molecular structure is called _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q027
frontText: What is the base unit of length in the SI system?
backText: The meter is the base unit of length in the SI system.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q028
backText: The newton is the unit for force.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q029
frontText: What unit measures energy, work, and quantity of heat?
backText: The joule measures energy, work, and quantity of heat.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q030
frontText: The amount of matter an object contains is called its _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q031
frontText: What is Newton’s first law of motion?
backText: An object at rest tends to stay at rest, and an object in motion tends to stay in motion with the same speed and in the same direction, unless acted upon by an unbalanced force.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q032
frontText: Sound waves are measured in what two units?
backText: Sound waves are measured in amplitude and wavelength.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q033
frontText: All wavelengths and frequencies of radiation are on the _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q034
backText: Refraction is the bending of light as it passes from one medium to another.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q035
backText: Reflection occurs when light bounces off an object.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q036
backText: Thermal equilibrium is a condition in which no heat is flowing between objects.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q037
frontText: What are the three ways heat energy transfers between objects?
backText: Heat energy transfers through conduction, convection, and radiation.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q038
frontText: What does the first law of thermodynamics say?
backText: The first law of thermodynamics says that energy can be neither created nor destroyed, but it can be transferred and converted.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q039
frontText: An element or molecule that results from a chemical reaction is called a _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q040
frontText: _____ is the study of Earth’s physical appearance.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q042
frontText: What is the solid rock below Earth’s crust called?
backText: The solid rock below Earth’s crust is called the mantle.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q043
frontText: What do scientists believe is in Earth’s core?
backText: Scientists believe Earth’s core contains iron and nickel.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q044
backText: A hypothesis is a testable explanation of why something happens.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q045
frontText: How do scientists test a hypothesis?
backText: Scientists test a hypothesis by experimenting and observing outcomes.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q046
frontText: What does the prefix milli- mean in the metric system?
backText: The metric prefix milli- means one-thousandth, or 0.001.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q047
frontText: What does the prefix centi- mean in the metric system?
backText: The metric prefix centi- means one-hundredth, or 0.01.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q048
frontText: What does the prefix deci- mean in the metric system?
backText: The metric prefix deci- means one-tenth, or 0.1.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q049
frontText: One foot is approximately equal to how many meters?

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q050
backText: An ecosystem is a biological community of interacting organisms and their environment.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q051
frontText: What do plants need to grow?
backText: Plants need adequate sunlight, good soil or environmental nutrients, the right temperatures, and water to grow.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q052
backText: Biodiversity is the term scientists use to talk about the variety of life within ecosystems.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q053
frontText: What are the classifications in the Linnaean taxonomic classification system?
backText: The eight classifications in the Linnaean taxonomic system are domain, kingdom, phylum, class, order, family, genus, and species.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q054
frontText: What are the kingdoms in the Linnaean taxonomic classification system?
backText: The six kingdoms in the Linnaean taxonomic system are animals, plants, fungi, protists, bacteria, and archaea.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q055
frontText: What is the nervous system responsible for?
backText: The nervous system is responsible for receiving, processing, and responding to physical stimuli.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q056
frontText: What is the respiratory system responsible for?
backText: The respiratory system is responsible for inhaling air, using oxygen from the air to release energy, and exhaling carbon dioxide.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q057
frontText: What is the purpose of the renal system?
backText: The renal system filters toxins out of the body.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q058
frontText: What are the three types of human muscles?
backText: The three types of human muscles are cardiac muscle, smooth muscle, and skeletal muscle.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q059
frontText: What are the six major types of bone joints?
backText: The six major types of bone joints are hinge joints, ball and socket joints, pivot joints, fixed joints, saddle joints, condyloid joints, and gliding joints.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q060
frontText: What do ligaments and tendons do?
backText: Ligaments join the bones, and tendons connect muscle tissue to bones and other structures in the body.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q061
frontText: What types of nutrients do animals need for fuel?
backText: Animals need carbohydrates, fats, fiber, minerals, protein, vitamins, and water for fuel.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q062
backText: vascular tissue, primary roots, and secondary roots (branches)

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q063
frontText: What does a plant’s root system do?
backText: A plant’s root system absorbs water and nutrients from the soil, holds the plant in place, and stores nutrients.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q064
frontText: What are the two stages of photosynthesis?
backText: The two stages of photosynthesis are light-dependent reactions and the Calvin cycle.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q065
frontText: Every cell has what four things in common?
backText: Every cell has a nucleus, cytoplasm, a membrane, and ribosomes.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q066
frontText: What is the function of a cell’s nucleus?
backText: A cell’s nucleus controls cellular activity and holds the cell’s genetic material (DNA).

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q067
frontText: What do plant cells contain that animal cells do not?
backText: Plant cells contain chloroplasts, which help plants create food with the help of sunlight.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q068
backText: Osmosis is the movement of liquid through the cell membrane (and the main way that water goes in and out of cells).

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q069
backText: Photosynthesis is the conversion of electromagnetic energy from the sun to chemical energy that the cell can use.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q070
backText: Kinetic energy is the energy a body possesses by virtue of being in motion.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q071
frontText: What are the four general blood types?
backText: The four general blood types are A, B, AB, and O.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q072
frontText: What are the eight planets in order of their distance from the sun, starting with the closest to the sun?
backText: The planet closest to the sun is Mercury, followed by Venus, Earth, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q073
frontText: What is the function of white blood cells?

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q074
frontText: The very rigid molecular structure of repeating patterns found in solids is called _____.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q075
frontText: What is water’s boiling point at sea level, in degrees Celsius and Fahrenheit?
backText: At sea level, the boiling point of water is 100 degrees Celsius and 212 degrees Fahrenheit.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q076
backText: When sublimation takes place, a substance changes from a solid to a gas without ever passing through a liquid phase.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q077
frontText: What is the rate of gravity on Earth?
backText: The rate of gravity on Earth is 9.8 meters per second.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q078
frontText: What is the formula for work in physics?
backText: , where W represents work, F represents force, and d represents displacement.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q079
frontText: What are the layers of the Earth, beginning with the outermost layer?
backText: The outermost layer of the Earth is the crust, followed by the mantle, outer core, and inner core.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q080
frontText: What are the layers of Earth’s mantle?
backText: The mantle’s layers are the mesosphere, asthenosphere, and lithosphere.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q081
backText: Sediment, such as particles of sand, seashells, and bone fragments that harden over time, is the basis of sedimentary rock.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q082
frontText: What causes metamorphic rock to form?
backText: Intense heat and pressure below Earth’s surface forms metamorphic rock.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q083
frontText: What is igneous rock made from?
backText: Igneous rock is made from cooled magma.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q084
backText: A fault line is space between Earth’s tectonic plates.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q085
frontText: What are the five oceans classified by scientists?
backText: The Atlantic, Pacific, Indian, Arctic, and Southern Oceans are the five oceans scientists classify.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q086
backText: Earth’s atmosphere is approximately 300 miles thick.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q087
frontText: In which layer of Earth’s atmosphere do most weather changes occur?
backText: Most of Earth’s weather changes happen in the troposphere.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q088
frontText: What is the most prevalent gas in Earth’s atmosphere?
backText: Nitrogen, at about 78 percent, is the most prevalent gas in Earth’s atmosphere.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q089
backText: Climate refers to patterns in weather over time (usually 30 years or more).

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q090
frontText: What three scales do scientists use to measure temperature?

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q091
frontText: What formula converts Celsius to Fahrenheit?

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q092
frontText: What are the major ways scientists determine the ages of fossils?
backText: Scientist determine fossil age through radiometric dating, relative dating, paleomagnetism, and biochronology.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q093
frontText: What’s at the center of the Milky Way galaxy?
backText: A supermassive black hole is at the center of the Milky Way.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q094
frontText: What type of star is Earth’s sun?
backText: The sun is a yellow dwarf star.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q095
backText: The inner four planets in Earth’s solar system are terrestrial (Earthlike) planets comprised mainly of iron and rock.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q096
backText: A meteoroid is a rock from space that hits Earth’s atmosphere and glows as it heats up.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q097
backText: DNA determines an organism’s traits and genetic makeup.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q098
frontText: What is the basic unit of mass or weight in the metric system?
backText: The gram is the basic unit of mass or weight in the metric system.

title: 476245 18-19ASVAB_FC2_Q099
frontText: What is a medium’s refractive index?
backText: A medium’s refractive index is the ratio by which light is slowed while passing through the medium.

title: 560746_1920ASVAB_FC2_100
backText: A cell’s ribosome is an organelle that processes genetic instructions so the cell can create proteins.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_001
frontText: What are the three ways in which electricity is measured?
backText: Electricity is measured in volts, amperes (amps), and ohms.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_002
backText: Electrical current is the flow of electrons moving from one place to another (specifically from negative to positive).

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_003
frontText: What does a watt measure in electricity?
backText: A watt measures power, the rate at which electrical energy is consumed or transformed into another type of energy.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_004
backText: A watt-hour is an amount of electrical energy used and relates power (watts) and time (hour).

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_005
frontText: What are the smallest particles that can be broken up without losing their original properties?
backText: Atoms are the smallest particles that can be broken up without losing their original properties.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_006
frontText: What two types of subatomic particles are in an atom’s nucleus?
backText: Protons and neutrons are inside an atom’s nucleus.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_007
frontText: What type of charge do electrons have?
backText: Electrons have a negative electrical charge.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_008
frontText: What does a substance’s atomic number tell you?
backText: An atomic number tells you how many protons are in the substance.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_009
frontText: What do the number of electrons in a valence shell determine?
backText: The number of electrons in a valence shell determine whether an object is a conductor, semiconductor, or insulator.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_010
frontText: What happens with electrons in a conductor?
backText: Conductors allow electrons to flow freely between different atoms.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_011
frontText: What happens with electrons in an insulator?
backText: Electrons don’t have much room to move in an insulator. That’s because an insulator has a mostly full valence shell.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_012
backText: A circuit is the path of an electrical current.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_013
frontText: What tools can measure voltage in a circuit?
backText: A voltmeter or multimeter measure voltage in a circuit.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_014
frontText: What is an electrical storage compartment in a battery called?
backText: A cell is an electrical storage compartment in a battery.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_015
frontText: How is electrical current (the flow of electrons) expressed?
backText: Current or flow of electrons is expressed in amperes (amps) which represent a charge (in coulombs) over a second.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_016
backText: A circuit breaker is a device that automatically interrupts the flow of an electrical current if there is an issue.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_017
backText: A rheostat is a device that can vary the resistance against a current flow without opening a circuit.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_018
backText: Ohm’s law says, “The current in a circuit is directly proportional to the applied voltage and inversely proportional to the circuit resistance.”

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_019
frontText: How do you express Ohm’s law in mathematical terms?
backText:

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_020
frontText: True or False: Most electrons will take the path of lowest resistance, but some will still take a path of higher resistance.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_021
frontText: What three components must a working circuit include?
backText: A working circuit must include a voltage source, a load, and conductors.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_022
frontText: What is a load in terms of electricity?
backText: In terms of electricity, a load is a source of resistance that converts electrical energy into another form of energy (like a lightbulb).

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_023
frontText: What happens to the electrical current if you flip a light switch from “On” to “Off”?
backText: When you flip a light switch from “On” to “Off,” you open the circuit to interrupt the flow of electrical current. As a result, the light turns off.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_024
backText: A fuse helps regulate electrical current. If the load is too great and the current heats up over a certain level, the fuse will disintegrate and interrupt the circuit to prevent damage throughout the electrical system.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_025
frontText: When can current flow through an insulator, such as air?
backText: Electrical current can flow through an insulator if there’s enough difference of potential, such as when lightning travels through the air to strike something on Earth’s surface.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_026
frontText: How many paths are there for an electrical current in a single series circuit?
backText: There is one path an electrical current can take in a single series circuit.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_027
frontText: How are loads wired in a parallel circuit?
backText: Each load is wired along its own path in a parallel circuit.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_028
frontText: What happens if there’s a break in an electrical current’s path in a series circuit?
backText: If there’s a break in an electrical current’s path in a series circuit, the electrical flow stops everywhere in the circuit.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_029
frontText: What happens if there’s a break in an electrical current’s path in a parallel circuit?
backText: If there’s a break in an electrical current’s path in a parallel circuit, the current flow stops in the path with a break; it continues to flow to other loads.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_030
frontText: What happens to the total resistance of a current if you add a load in parallel?
backText: Adding a load in parallel decreases the total resistance of a current because it provides an additional pathway for electrons to take.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_031
frontText: What is the most common circuit configuration for a home’s electrical system?
backText: Most homes are wired with series-parallel circuits.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_032
backText: A short circuit occurs when any wire accidentally crosses over another wire, causing the electricity to bypass the rest of the circuit and not follow its intended path.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_033
frontText: In a wire, where are the magnetic lines of force?
backText: Magnetic lines of force are perpendicular to the conductor and parallel to each other in a wire.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_034
frontText: In how many directions can direct current flow?
backText: Direct current can only (and always) flow in one direction.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_035
frontText: True or False: Alternating current constantly changes direction in a regular pattern.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_036
frontText: What type of current enters your home from the power company?
backText: The power company supplies alternating current to your home.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_037
frontText: What does a grounding wire do?
backText: A grounding wire gives excess electricity a place to go when it’s displaced from its original path.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_038
frontText: What is the measure for the number of times an alternating current changes direction in one second?
backText: The number of times an alternating current changes direction per second is known as its frequency, which is measured in Hertz (Hz).

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_039
backText: Capacitive reactance is a measure of a capacitor’s opposition to alternating current, and it’s measured in ohms. Don’t confuse this with capacitance, which is the storage of energy measured in farads.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_040
backText: Inductive reactance is a measure of the resistance to a change in the flow of current, and it’s measured in ohms. Don’t confuse this with inductance, which is measured in henrys.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_041
frontText: How can you express impedance in mathematical terms?
backText: You express impedance as the ration of electromotive force to a current like this:

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_042
backText: A capacitor stores or holds a charge of electrons.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_043
backText: A semiconductor diode is a component made of a material with conductivity somewhere between that of a conductor and an insulator.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_044
backText: A rectifier changes alternating current to direct current.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_045
frontText: What are the three basic terminals on a transistor?
backText: The three basic terminals on a transistor are the emitter, the base, and the collector.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_046
frontText: What does a block diagram show?
backText: A block diagram shows the combined circuits that form a complex system.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_047
frontText: What function do wires perform in an electrical system?
backText: Wires pass current from one part of the system to another.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_048
backText: A transducer converts energy from one form to another.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_049
backText: An inductor is a wire coil that creates a magnetic field when current passes through it.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_050
frontText: What numbers do black, brown, and red markings represent on nonvariable resistors?
backText: Black is 0, brown is 1, and red is 2.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_051
backText: A potentiometer is a type of variable resistor with three contacts that’s used to control voltage.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_052
backText: A diode allows electricity to flow in only one direction; they’re similar to a valve.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_053
backText: An antenna is a device designed to receive and/or transmit radio signals.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_054
frontText: What does a circuit diagram show you?
backText: A circuit diagram shows you how electronic components are connected to each other.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_055
frontText: What color are positive DC wires?

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_056
frontText: What color are negative DC wires?

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_057
frontText: What color(s) are DC ground wires?
backText: DC ground wires can be white or gray.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_058
backText: Green wires can be live if there’s a fault in an electrical system that causes electricity to take another path. This is because green wires normally go to ground.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_059
frontText: What should you assume about all electrical wires?
backText: You should assume that all electrical wires are live, regardless of how they’re labeled or what color they are.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_060
backText: Current flows from a negative pole to a positive pole.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_061
frontText: What is the symbol for ohms?
backText: The symbol that represents ohms is .

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_062
frontText: Which object supplies the least resistance to an electrical current: wood, rubber or copper?
backText: Copper offers the least resistance, which is why it’s used in electrical wiring.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_091
frontText: What units are used to measure the rate of electrons moving through a conductor?
backText: Electrons moving through a conductor are measured in amperes.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_092
frontText: If a diagram mentions 55 cycles per second, what is its equivalent in hertz?
backText: Cycles per second is the same thing as hertz, so 55 cycles per second equals 55 Hz.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_093
backText: Electrical resistance is opposition to the flow of current.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_094
backText: Electrical potential is another (and older) term for voltage.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_095
frontText: What is the unit you use to measure electrical charge transported by current of one ampere in one second?
backText: A coulomb is the unit of electrical charge that moves in a current of one amp in one second.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_096
frontText: What measures current in a circuit?
backText: An ammeter measures current in a circuit.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_097
backText: Electromotive force is another word for voltage, which is electric potential.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_099
backText: is the mathematical expression of Ohm’s law.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC4_100
frontText: What type of device would you use to reduce the current in an electrical circuit?
backText: A resistor reduces the current in an electrical circuit.

frontText: When two or more forces interact so their combination cancels each other out, what state are they in?

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_002
frontText: If an object is at rest, what does it tend to do unless some other force acts upon it?

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_003
backText: Pressure is the measurement of force over a specified area.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_004
frontText: What is the formula for deriving pressure?

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_005
backText: Friction is a force that resists the motion of two objects or surfaces that touch.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_006
backText: Magnetism is the attractive or repulsive force from a permanent magnet or motion of electrical charge, such as the property of attracting iron or steel with a magnet.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_007
backText: Mass measures how much matter an object contains.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_008
frontText: What does an object’s weight measure?
backText: Weight is a measure of the force that gravity exerts on an object.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_009
backText: Density measures how much matter is inside an object (its mass) and how much space that matter takes up (its volume).

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_010
backText: Velocity is the speed and direction in which an object moves.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_011
frontText: What is the mathematical formula to determine force?

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_012
frontText: What is Newton’s law of universal gravitation?
backText: Newton’s law of universal gravitation says that every object in the universe attracts every other object in the universe.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_013
frontText: What units are used to measure tension force?
backText: Tension force is measured in newtons (N) or pounds-force. These are also the units for all forces.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_014
frontText: What is the buildup of electrical charges on the surface of a substance?
backText: The buildup of electrical charges on the surface of a substance is called static electricity.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_015
frontText: What is the formula for work?

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_017
frontText: What is the energy of motion called?
backText: The energy of motion is called kinetic energy.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_018
frontText: What is Newton’s first law of motion?
backText: Newton’s first law of motion states, “An object at rest stays at rest and an object in motion stays in motion with the same speed and in the same direction unless acted upon by an unbalanced force.”

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_019
frontText: What is the force that’s produced when two surfaces rub together?
backText: The force that’s produced when two surfaces rub together is called frictional resistance (but you can just call it friction for short).

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_020
frontText: What are the two main ingredients in work?
backText: The two main factors necessary for work to be done are force and displacement.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_021
frontText: What is the definition of power?
backText: Power is the rate at which work is done.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_022
frontText: What is the formula to calculate power?

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_023
frontText: What unit is work measured in when using the formula ?
backText: Work is measured in joules when using the formula .

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_024
frontText: What unit is time measured in when using the formula ?
backText: Time is measured in seconds when using the formula .

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_025
frontText: What unit is power measured in when using the formula ?
backText: Power is measured in watts when using the formula .

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_026
frontText: When measuring power in machines using , what unit usually represents power?
backText: Horsepower is usually the way people measure work that machines, such as cars, do. One horsepower equals 745.7 watts.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_027
frontText: What are the two formulas used to calculate mechanical advantage?
backText: and are the two formulas used to calculate mechanical advantage. and are the two formulas used to calculate mechanical advantage.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_028
frontText: How much more work does a machine with a mechanical advantage of 2 allow you to do with the same amount of effort?
backText: A machine with a mechanical advantage of 2 lets you do two times the work with the same amount of effort.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_029
frontText: What type of machine is a seesaw at a playground?
backText: A seesaw at a playground is a type of lever.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_030
frontText: What formula determines how much a lever reduces the amount of effort necessary to do work?
backText: tells you how much effort is necessary to do work with a lever.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_031
frontText: What formula do you use to calculate mechanical advantage with a lever?

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_032
frontText: What is the mechanical advantage of a lever with an effort arm that’s 10 inches long and a resistance arm that’s 5 inches long?
backText: Use the formula and replace the lengths of the lever’s arms with the appropriate numbers. The mechanical advantage of this lever is 2.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_033
frontText: What is the mechanical advantage of a lever with an effort arm that’s 9 inches long and a resistance arm that’s 3 inches long?
backText: Use the formula and replace the lengths of the lever’s arms with the appropriate numbers. The mechanical advantage of this lever is 3.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_034
frontText: Where is the fulcrum on a Class 1 lever?
backText: The fulcrum on a Class 1 lever is between the effort and the load.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_035
frontText: Where is the load on a Class 2 lever?
backText: The load on a Class 2 lever is between the effort and the fulcrum.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_036
frontText: Where is the fulcrum on a Class 3 lever?
backText: The fulcrum on a Class 3 lever is beside the effort, opposite the load.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_037
frontText: What types of levers are pliers, scissors, and boat oars?
backText: Pliers, scissors and boat oars are Class 1 levers.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_038
frontText: What types of levers are wheelbarrows, crowbars, and nutcrackers?
backText: Wheelbarrows, crowbars and nutcrackers are Class 2 levers.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_039
frontText: What types of levers are tweezers, staplers, and brooms?
backText: Tweezers, staplers, and brooms are Class 3 levers.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_043
frontText: What formula do you use to calculate the mechanical advantage of a ramp?
backText: Use to calculate the mechanical advantage of a ramp.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_044
frontText: What types of machines are screws?
backText: Screws are inclined planes in spiral form.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_045
frontText: What do pulleys and gears change?
backText: Pulleys and gears can change the magnitude (size) and direction of force.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_046
frontText: What type of pulley is depicted?
backText: This type of pulley is a block and tackle system with a 2 to 1 advantage.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_047
frontText: If you have an even number of gears connected in a series, do the first and last gears turn in the same direction or opposite directions?
backText: With an even number of gears in a series, the first and last gear turn in opposite directions of each other.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_048
frontText: If you have an odd number of gears connected in a series, do the first and last gears turn in the same direction or in opposite directions?
backText: When you have an odd number of gears connected in a series, the first and last gears turn in the same direction.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_049
frontText: What determines the speed at which a gear turns?
backText: The number of teeth on a gear determine how fast it turns.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_050
frontText: If Gear 1 has six teeth and Gear 2 has 7 teeth, which gear will turn faster?
backText: Gear 1 will rotate faster than Gear 2. The fewer teeth a gear has, the faster it rotates.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_051
frontText: What ratio can you use to express the relation of teeth in these two gears?
backText: The relation of teeth in this arrangement is 6:8, which you can reduce to 3:4.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_052
frontText: When paired with a gear with six teeth, how many revolutions does a gear with eight teeth make by the time the six-toothed gear has made one revolution?
backText: A gear with 8 teeth will make a rotation when connected with a gear with six teeth that makes one complete rotation.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_053
frontText: What type of gears connect shafts at different angles (not parallel)?
backText: You can use a bevel gears to connect shafts at different angles.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_054
backText: Pulleys are used to transmit motion from one location to another. When used as part of a system they can reduce the force required to lift a weight.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_055
frontText: What determines how fast a pulley rotates?
backText: A pulley’s diameter in relation to the pulley that’s driving it determines how fast it rotates.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_056
frontText: What ratio expresses the relation between these pulleys if A has a radius of 1, B has a radius of 2 and C has a radius of 4?
backText: The ratio of these pulleys is 1:2:4.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_057
frontText: Which pulley turns the slowest in this arrangement?
backText: Pulley C rotates the slowest because it’s the largest.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_058
frontText: What does a wheel-and-axle machine do to the effort you use?
backText: A wheel-and-axle machine multiplies the effort you use and produces a greater force.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_059
frontText: What type of machine is a car’s steering wheel?
backText: A car’s steering wheel is a wheel-and-axle machine.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_060
backText: Torque is a twisting or turning force that tends to cause rotation around an axis. Another name for a torque is a moment.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_061
backText: Torque is measured in newton-meters or pound-feet.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_062
backText: A vise is a machine that holds something in place with great force.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_063
frontText: What type of fluid is inside a hydraulic jack?
backText: A hydraulic jack uses a nearly incompressible liquid, such as oil.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_064
frontText: What is the mechanical advantage in a hydraulic jack that has one cylinder with a 1-inch diameter and one cylinder with a 4-inch diameter?
backText: The mechanical advantage of a hydraulic jack that has one cylinder with a 1-inch diameter and one cylinder with a 4-inch diameter is 4.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_065
frontText: What is the purpose of lubricating oil in an engine?
backText: Lubricating oil reduces friction between moving parts.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_066
frontText: What measures how much matter an object contains?
backText: Mass is the measurement that tells you how much matter an object contains.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_067
frontText: What two values do you need to know to calculate an object’s weight?
backText: You need to know an object’s mass and the value of the gravitational force acting upon it to calculate its weight. The formula you use is .

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_068
frontText: Rank these materials by density, with the highest density first: packing peanuts, iron, water, and ice cubes.
backText: From most-dense to least-dense, these materials are iron, water, ice cubes, and packing peanuts. (Did ice throw you off? It floats on water because it’s less dense than water is. The water is more dense, so it forces the ice to the top. On the other side of the coin, iron is more dense than water is, so it sinks to the bottom.)

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_069
frontText: What does Einstein’s theory of special relativity, , tell you?
backText: says that mass and energy are the same physical entity, and that they can be changed into each other.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_070
frontText: What does the m represent in ?
backText: The m represents an object’s mass.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_071
frontText: What does c represent in ?
backText: The c represents the speed of light.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_072
frontText: What is the unit of measure for force?
backText: Force is measured in newtons or pounds-force.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_073
frontText: What is the acceleration of gravity on Earth’s surface?

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_074
frontText: If you’re playing tug-of-war, and your side is pulling with a force of 100 N and the other side is pulling with a force of 80 N, what is the net force?
backText: The net force is 20 N, which is the difference between both sides.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_075
frontText: What does Newton’s Third Law of Motion say?
backText: Newton’s Third Law of Motion states that for every action (force) in nature, there’s an equal and opposite reaction.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_076
frontText: What state is an object in when two or more forces interacting on it cancel each other out?
backText: When two or more forces interact so that their combination cancels the other(s) out, the object is in a state of equilibrium.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_077

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_078
frontText: If you exert 100 pounds of force on a 100-square-inch surface, what is the amount of pressure?
backText: Using , 100 pounds of force on a 100-square-inch surface, you exert 1 pound per square inch (psi).

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_079
frontText: If a box weighs 150 pounds and you place it on the floor, where it occupies 25 square inches, how much pressure is it exerting on the floor?
backText: Using , the box is exerting a pressure of 6 pounds per square inch on the floor.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_080
backText: A barometer is a gauge that measures atmospheric pressure.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_081
frontText: What is the normal atmospheric pressure on Earth’s surface?
backText: The normal atmospheric pressure on Earth’s surface is about 14.7 psi.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_082
backText: Applied force is a force applied to an object by a person or another object.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_083
backText: Tension is transmitted through string, rope, cable, or wire when forces are acting on opposite ends.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_084
backText: Recoil occurs when something regains its original form when an object exerting force on it is removed.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_085
backText: Electrical force is the production of stationary electrical charges, often the result of friction.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_086
frontText: Who was the first famous mathematician to study gravity seriously?
backText: Sir Isaac Newton was the first mathematician to study gravity seriously.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_087
frontText: What is Newton’s Law of Universal Gravitation?
backText: Newton’s Law of Universal Gravitation is a law that states that every object in the universe attracts every other object in the universe.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_088
frontText: What are the two key factors in Newton’s Law of Universal Gravitation?
backText: Mass and distance are the two key factors in Newton’s Law of Universal Gravitation.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_089
frontText: What are the three main components that determine the amount of centrifugal force an object experiences?
backText: The three main components that determine an amount of centrifugal force are mass, (rotation) speed, and distance from the center of the rotating object.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_090
frontText: What units are used to measure tension force?
backText: Tension force is measured in pounds-force or Newtons (N).

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_091
frontText: Why is it easier to move a trunk across a smooth, icy surface than it is to move it along shag carpet?
backText: Smooth ice produces less friction than shag carpet does, so it’s easier to move a trunk across the ice.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_092
frontText: What can you use to decrease friction between two objects?
backText: Lubrication decreases friction between two objects.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_093
backText: In most substances, there are equal numbers of spinning electrons. Half spin in one direction and half spin in the other, which cancels out their magnetism.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_094
frontText: If someone moves a box 10 meters horizontally with a force of 20 N, how much work is done on the box?
backText: Using , the work done on the box is 200 joules.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_096
frontText: How much work do you exert on an object if you move it with a force of 50 newtons and it travels a distance of 2 meters?
backText: Using the formula , you can determine that the amount of work you exerted on the object is 100 joules.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_097
frontText: What is the mechanical advantage of a block and tackle system that can lift a box weighing 1,000 newtons with 100 newtons of input force?
backText: Using , the mechanical advantage of the block and tackle system is 10.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_098
frontText: What is the mechanical advantage of a machine that can move a 150-newton object with an input force of 25 newtons?
backText: Using , you can calculate that the mechanical advantage of this machine is 6.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_099
frontText: If two round balls, one measuring 2 cm in diameter and the other measuring 10 cm in diameter, when both have the same density, roll toward each other at the same speed, what will happen when they collide?
backText: The 10-cm ball will slow down but continue in the same direction. The smaller ball will be pushed backward. This is because the larger ball has more momentum.

title: 784173_2122ASVAB_FC5_100
frontText: If 17 gears are arranged in a series, and the first gear turns clockwise, what direction will the last gear turn?
backText: If you have an odd number of gears aligned in a series, the first and last gear spin in the same direction, so if Gear 1 turns clockwise, Gear 17 rotates clockwise.
